\begin_layout Abstract
This paper proposes a method combining revealed preference theory and machine learning ideas to partition consumers in a principled way.
 The Generalized Axiom of Revealed Preference can be applied to partition consumers into fully rational types,
 in the classical consumer theory sense.
 From here,
 I construct a schedule between parsimony and rationality:
 for each number of types,
 households are partitioned into groups that are as close to rational as possible.
 I illustrate using household milk purchase data.
 In the example data,
 15 types are required to fully rationalize the data;
 however,
 many of these have few households,
 and far fewer types describe the data at little cost to rationality.
 My method thus establishes a theory-driven and principled way to describe consumer demand data and the tradeoff between parsimony and heterogeneity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gary Becker famously advocated for an approach to economics embracing assumptions of maximizing behavior,
 stable preferences,
 and equilibrium:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The assumption of stable preferences provides a stable foundation for generating predictions about responses to various changes,
 and prevents the analyst from succumbing to the temptation of simply postulating the required shift in preferences to 'explain' all apparent contradictions to his predictions.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Becker"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply,
 if economics is a science,
 then unexplained phenomena must not be consistently hand-waved away as unique phenomena.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SB97"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 are even more stark:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Tastes neither change capriciously nor differ importantly between people.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 this poses a problem for the estimation of consumer behavior,
 where significant individual heterogeneity is natural.
 While some of this heterogeneity can be modeled on the consumers' observables (e.g.
 wealth,
 demographics,
 etc.),
 the majority is an accident of nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given consumption data from a panel of households,
 the classic approach is to pool the data,
 and control on household observables if available.
 An early example,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BBL"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 finds that the approach works well for some categories of purchases but very poorly for others.
 They apply the (quadratic) almost ideal demand system,
 which explicitly assumes a representative consumer.
 More recent models like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BLP"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 allow random coefficients to incorporate individual heterogeneity (among other desiderata).
 Nevertheless,
 when households have significant unobservable heterogeneity,
 the resulting estimates may be imprecise;
 and point estimates may not accurately describe any households at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CP"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 propose to apply revealed preferences,
 chiefly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Afriat"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Varian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 to partition households into fully rational types.
 Afriat's theorem establishes the Generalized Axiom of Revealed Preference (GARP) as a necessary and sufficient condition for a set of consumption data to be generated by a well-behaved utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Given an observed choice 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 at a price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 it must dominate any other affordable choice.
 The following is an example of a violation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 was chosen at price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 was chosen at price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}\geq p_{1}x_{2}$
\end_inset

 – that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 was affordable when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 was chosen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}x_{2}\geq p_{2}x_{1}$
\end_inset

 – that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 was affordable when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 was chosen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At least one of the inequalities is strict
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This violation implies a cycle in preferences,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\succeq x_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\succeq x_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 with at least one strict.
 GARP generalizes this idea from 2-cycles to general length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GARP is usually interpreted as a check on repeated observations from one individual (household).
 Crawford and Pendakur propose to use GARP to partition household data into rational types.
 That is,
 they ask 
\emph on
how many distinct utility functions are generating the consumer demand data?

\emph default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I apply this method to data from the USDA,
 National Household Food Acquisition and Purchase Survey (FoodAPS).
 I find that 15 types are necessary to rationalize the 2,167 households.
 However,
 many of these types contain very few households.
 I thus construct a schedule between the number of types and rationality:
 for each number of types,
 households are partitioned into that many groups by a greedy algorithm that places each household so as to keep the partition as rational as possible,
 with rationality measured by either the Critical Cost Efficiency Index (CCEI) or the Varian index (cf.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Afriat73"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Varian90"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The schedule makes the tradeoff explicit:
 sacrificing a modest amount of rationality (interpretable as unmodeled individual heterogeneity) supports far fewer types.
 My method thus offers intermediate options between two extremes – assuming all households have the same underlying utility;
 or requiring full rationality.
 By sacrificing a modest amount of rationality (interpretable as requiring individual heterogeneity),
 we require far fewer types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next section describes the dataset.
 Section 3 describes the proposed method to partition the households into groups.
 Section 4 estimates demand via almost ideal demand system (AIDS).
 Section 5 concludes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate my proposed method,
 I use data from the USDA FoodAPS survey,
 which was fielded from April 2012 through mid-January 2013.
 Each participating household reported the foods that household members acquired over a 7-day period.
 The final analytic sample was 4,826 households.
 I focus particularly on household milk purchases,
 partitioned into four types of milk:
 whole,
 2%,
 1%,
 and skim/nonfat milk.
 Among the survey sample,
 2,167 households are observed purchasing any milk;
 this forms my sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each household,
 I observe the quantity of each type of milk purchased and the prices at which they were purchased.
 Prices were generally not recorded for goods not purchased;
 thus I impute prices when not recorded by the median in the matching category:
 region,
 rural / urban status,
 and store type.
 While FoodAPS level of observations is a purchase event (e.g.
 one receipt),
 I aggregate each household to a weekly sum.
 Table 1 summarizes the data.
 Note the extreme outlier shown in the maximum price of whole milk.
 I chose to leave this observation in the dataset,
 as the objective of this paper is to illustrate my proposed method,
 rather than to accurately estimate milk demand.
\end_layout

