\begin_layout Standard
Motivated by this pattern,
 we may ask how much we gain in terms of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rationality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by having these small groups.
 Stated another way,
 do we lose much by merging some groups into others?
 Doing comes with the practical advantage of allowing us to estimate fewer demand models;
 and the philosophical advantage of respecting Stigler's and Becker's charge of limiting capricious changes in taste.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course,
 when we combine groups,
 by definition they must become non-rationalizable.
 That is,
 treating the households in the combined group as coming from a single utility function means that some of them behave irrationally.
 A number of indexes exist to quantify the degree of irrationality.
 In this paper,
 I use the critical cost efficiency index (CCEI) and the related Varian index.
 Intuitively,
 CCEI asks 
\emph on
how much would we need to shrink each observed budget before the consumer’s choices become consistent with utility maximization?

\emph default
 A 
\begin_inset Formula $CCEI=1$
\end_inset

 is completely rational;
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $CCEI=0.95$
\end_inset

 is rational after allowing up to 5% of each household's budget to be wasted.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I now turn to my proposed algorithm,
 which produces a schedule between the number of types and rationality.
 For a set of households 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{G}$
\end_inset

 denote its CCEI when all of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is treated as one type.
 I define the rationality of a partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{G_{1},...,G_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 as the minimum group CCEI,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\min_{G\in\mathcal{P}}e_{G}$
\end_inset

:
 the common efficiency level at which every group simultaneously passes the (relaxed) GARP test.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each number of types 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 I find the highest efficiency level at which 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 types suffice.
 For a level 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 relax GARP as in the CCEI's definition and run Crawford and Pendakur's upper bound algorithm under the relaxed relations (keeping the best of five random orders):
 this bounds the number of types needed at that level.
 The number of types needed weakly rises with 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

,
 so the highest feasible level for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is found by binary search over the finite set of candidate levels — the cost ratios of the data.
 This mirrors Crawford and Pendakur's treatment of optimisation error,
 with the roles of the efficiency level and the number of types interchanged.
 Finally,
 each group's CCEI in the chosen partition is computed exactly,
 and the reported rationality is their minimum,
 which is at least the search level;
 the fully rationalizing 15-type partition guarantees full rationality at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=15$
\end_inset

.
 The schedule is weakly increasing in the number of types by construction,
 since the set of feasible levels only grows as more types are allowed.
 Lower rationality is interpretable as requiring more individual heterogeneity to rationalize the data.
 Algorithm 3 summarizes the procedure;
 the Varian variant instead assigns each household the largest multiplier consistent with its group,
 as described below.
\end_layout

