\begin_layout Standard
I also repeat the analysis for the Varian index,
 which allows each household to waste an individual amount of its budget.
 Here each household carries its own efficiency multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

:
 when a household is assigned,
 it receives the largest multiplier consistent with its group,
 and existing members keep theirs.
 The reported rationality at each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the simple average of the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 across all households.
 The resulting measure is smoother and less punishing,
 since one badly-behaved household no longer drags down its whole group.
 Computing the Varian index exactly is NP-hard (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DR"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an exact mixed-integer programming approach);
 the tracked multipliers are feasible by construction,
 so the reported index is a slightly conservative lower bound.
 Figure 3 shows the schedule of Varian index rationality to number of types.

