\begin_layout Section
Demand estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incorporating individual heterogeneity into demand estimation is difficult;
 see for example 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Matzkin"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 the almost ideal demand system (AIDS) is easy to estimate,
 at the cost of assuming away individual heterogeneity.
 The previous section's method offers a principled way to quantify the size of this assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate,
 I estimates AIDS models by type.
 For household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and milk type 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 the share equation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{i}^{j}=\alpha_{j}+\sum_{k=1}^{4}\gamma_{jk}\ln p_{i}^{k}+\beta_{j}\ln\left(\frac{x_{i}}{P_{i}}\right)+\varepsilon_{i}^{j}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln P_{i}=\alpha_{0}+\sum_{k}\alpha_{k}\ln p_{i}^{k}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k}\sum_{\ell}\gamma_{kl}\ln p_{i}^{k}\ln p_{i}^{l}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}^{j}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's share of the milk budget spent on 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{j}$
\end_inset

 is the price of milk 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 faced by household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Prices and expenditures are normalized so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p^{j}=\ln x=0$
\end_inset

 at the median household.
 Restrictions are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\alpha_{k}=1$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\beta_{k}=0$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j}\gamma_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 – expenditure shares over milk categories sum to 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k}\gamma_{jk}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 – homogeneity of degree zero in prices and total expenditure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{jk}=\gamma_{kj}$
\end_inset

 – symmetry of the Slutsky matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{j}$
\end_inset

 are interpreted as predicted budget shares at the median prices and expenditure.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{j}$
\end_inset

 is expenditure semi-elasticity of the share,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial w_{j}/\partial\ln x$
\end_inset

;
 that is,
 the change in 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's share of the budget per log change in total milk expenditure.
 Intuitively,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{j}>0$
\end_inset

 implies milk 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is a luxury,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{j}<0$
\end_inset

 implies it is a necessity.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{kl}$
\end_inset

 is the change in the share of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 per unit change in the log of the price of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln p^{l}$
\end_inset

,
 holding real expenditure fixed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 3 shows AIDS 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 estimates for partition into 8 types (according to the CCEI procedure) as an example.
 The pooled sample estimates are incorrect on theoretical grounds (since we know we cannot treat all households as sharing a common utility function).
 Further,
 in practical terms,
 the estimates mask considerable heterogeneity.
 The pooled estimates are unsurprisingly close to the largest type,
 Type 1.
 But other large groups show very different behavior in both preferred milk and price responses.
 For example,
 Type 3 purchases almost exclusively 2% milk,
 but shows a modest negative expenditure semi-elasticity for it.
\end_layout

